<h1> Cannibalism was a potent symbol for the people of Early Modern Europe </h1>
<p> Nearly all cases of werewolf trials involved the accusation of cannibalism. The visual images and trial testimony
 linger on the grisly physical act of devouring. Where cannibalism itself is absent, 
such as in some of the trials from Lorraine, it is hinted at symbolically. The destruction of livestock, through violent
physical attack as well as sickness, exchanges one sort of forbidden eating for another. Sheep, like children, are being
attacked and consumed through the abherrant hunger of the wolf-sorcerer. This imagery is no accident, and it reveals
what made the werewolf such a potent symbol, and terrifying threat, to accusers. </p>
