<p>
The werewolf refresented an ultimate form of "deviant other" to the people of 15th-17th century Western Europe. One of the key
ways was through cannibalism, which had long marked the "deviant other," in the symbolic world of Western Europe.
</p>
<h1> Boiled or Raw? </h1>
<p> Early Modern witches were also deeply linked, through visual art, testimony and literature, to cannibalism, particularly
child-eating. Their child-eating, however, was very different from the werewolf, as closer examination shows. </p>
